{"questionId":"9082293","questionHtml":"<p>A simple pendulum has a time period <em><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>T</mi></math></em> on the Earth. The pendulum is taken to the Moon&nbsp;where the gravitational field strength is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>6</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;that of the Earth.</p>\n<p>What is the time period of the pendulum on the Moon?</p>\n<p>A.&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>T</mi><msqrt><mn>6</mn></msqrt></math></p>\n<p>B.&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>T</mi></math></p>\n<p>C.&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msqrt><mn>6</mn></msqrt><mn>6</mn></mfrac><mi>T</mi></math></p>\n<p>D.&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>T</mi><mn>6</mn></mfrac></math></p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>A</p>","meta":{"questionId":"9082293","referenceCode":"22M.1A.SL.TZ2.29","subjectId":"59-dp-physics-first-assessment-2025","title":"A simple pendulum has a time period T on the Earth. The pendulum is taken to the Moon where the gravitational field strength is 16 that of the Earth. What is the time period of the","paper":"1A","level":"SL","questionNumber":"29","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["D. Fields","D.1 Gravitational fields","C. Wave behaviour","C.1 Simple harmonic motion"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}